{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Legilimens| type=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic#Spells|Spell]]| features=Initiates [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Legilimency|Legilimency]]| appearance=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Order_of_the_Phoenix|''Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix'']]}}
== Overview ==
The '''''Legilimens''''' spell initiates [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Legilimency|Legilimency]], the process of reading thoughts and feelings from a subject.
== Extended Description ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Harry Potter|Harry]] first encounters this spell when learning [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Occlumency|Occlumency]] from Professor [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Severus Snape|Snape]]. [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Legilimency|Legilimency]] is the process of reading thoughts and feelings from a subject. A wizard or witch may use [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Legilimency|Legilimency]] to tell if someone is lying to them. [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Lord Voldemort|Lord Voldemort]] is especially skilled at detecting lies using [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Legilimency|Legilimency]]. This may be countered by a wizard or witch if he or she is a skilled Occlumens, that is, skilled in [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Occlumency|Occlumency]]. [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Severus Snape|Professor Snape]] appears to be proficient at legilimency and is definitely an accomplished Occlumens, even able to lie to [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Lord Voldemort|Lord Voldemort]].
